The problem you are facing is, that your `Plant` class and your `Flower` class each have their own `type`. And since you don&#39;t [override](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/IandI/override.html) the `getType()` method in your `Flower` class the return value will always be the `type` of `Plant` which is `null`.

You have some options to solve that problem. Either you do the same thing you did with `plot` where you make the field `protected` and assign it in the constructor of `Flower`.

```java
public class Plant {
    protected List&lt;String&gt; plot;
    protected String type;

    public Plant() {
        this.plot = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    }

    public String getType() {
        return this.type;
    }
}

public class Flower extends Plant {
    private int size;

    public Flower(String type) {
        this.type = type;
        this.size = 0;
    }
}
```

Or since every `Plant` has a `type` you could use the &quot;cleaner&quot; version, where you use [super](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/IandI/super.html) to let `Plant` handle the assignment.

```java
public class Plant {
    protected String type;
    protected List&lt;String&gt; plot;

    public Plant(String type) {
        this.type = type;
        this.plot = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    }

    public String getType() {
        return this.type;
    }
}

public class Flower extends Plant {
    private int size;

    public Flower(String type) {
        super(type);
        this.size = 0;
    }
}
```

